 than oxygen on Pt.
 Due to this high sticking coefficient, every free site on the sample will
 be imidiately occupied by CO once the sample is exposed to the reacting
 gas.
 The lack of free sites on the sample prevents oxygen from adsorbing on
 the catalyst and prevents the catalytic conversion.
 When the temperature of the sample is increased, the residence time of
 CO on the sample will get shorter and shorter, and eventually the oxygen
 will gain access to free Pt-sites.
 Once this happens, the oxygen will react with the CO according to the very
 simple reaction equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{2CO}+\mbox{O}_{2}\rightarrow\mbox{CO}_{2}
\]

\end_inset

this oxygen molecule will thus burn off two CO molecules and leave CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 which has an extremely short residence time on Pt, thus leaving two additional
 free sites.
 These new free sites will provide room for even more oxygen molecules and
 it is easy to imagine how the Pt surface will 'ignite' and react off all
 CO very suddenly.
 This phenomenon is what is known as lightoff and it has a clear experimental
 signature in the form of an extremely sudden onset of the reaction as well
 as significant temperature hysterises due to the fact that when the sample
 cools down it still has all the free sites and thus it will sustain conversion
 to far lower temperatures than the ignition temperature.
