\begin_layout Section
Lessones to be learned
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Besides the obviously interesting point in measureing how high the turn-over
 frequency can actually be, this results also put focus on the fact that
 extremely small amounts of catalyst can be responsible for much reactivity.
 In the case of the microreactors this is important in at least two ways.
 First of all it means, that we must be extremely carefull to avoid any
 kind of metal pollution in the reactor, especially platinum.
 This can be slightly more tricky that it sounds, since in the cleanroom,
 metal pollution in never far away, and we actually have seen examples of
 metal pollution in the reactors with any attempt to find the source being
 fruitless.
 Also, one should remeber that we have the heater on the backside of the
 reactor, which is made of Pt.
 It is of crucial importantance to be able to deposit this heater without
 even trace amount of Pt finding its way to the other side of the reactor.
 This is ensured by e-beam evaporating the Pt through a shadow mask.
 Other ways of depositing the heaters also exists, but these techniques
 often involves various wet-chemistry steps which means that small amounts
 of Pt could find its way from the backside to the frontside through the
 liquid fase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The other important lesson to be learned is that one should be extremely
 carefull when trying to apply in-situ methods.
 Even though in-situ methods is not easy to apply in a microreactor, we
 are continously considering our options in this field, since this would
 significantly increase the usefullness of the microreactors.
 However, even in the rather optimistic case, that we actually do succeed
 in finding methods that would provide in-situ information, the fact that
 such small areas of the reactor might, at least in some cases, be responsible
 for all the conversion.
 This means that whatever technique is being applied might primarily sample
 areas of the sample that is not actually doing the conversion.
 A technique with low spatial resolution might be easy to measure on the
 converting part of catalyst, but the signal to noise ration will be poor,
 potentially too low to see anyting.
 A technique with better spatial resolution will give a much better signal
 to noise, but faces the where real risk of not seeing the relevant part
 of the sample at all.
\end_layout

